Learning outcomes
By the end of the course, students should be able to:

explain how linkage, composition, reconstruction, and membership-inference attacks defeat informal privacy protections;
interpret differential privacy as a bound on an adversary’s ability to distinguish neighboring datasets;
construct an empirical privacy audit and state correctly what its lower bound does and does not prove;
calculate or bound sensitivity, choose a private mechanism, and reason about composition and post-processing;
diagnose the statistical failure of a private method and redesign its utility measure, clipping rule, support requirement, or point of noise injection;
compare private statistical and machine-learning methods using both privacy status and common- footing utility measures; and
evaluate a private synthetic-data method in terms of its privacy contract, preserved relationships, intended analytical workload, and failure modes.

For current materials and logistics, start with the course overview.
